<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-05-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="211" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Lord
                                    <persName type="to">Pauncefote</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-05-09"><hi rend="italic">May 9,
                                1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2150.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: In reply to your note No. 102, of
                            the 24th ultimo, I have the honor to inform you that it is stated in a
                            letter of the 6th instant from the Acting Secretary of the Navy that
                            that Department has had communication with Rear-Admiral Remy, and that
                            it is now in a position to say that the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Brooklyn</hi> will visit New Zealand after the completion of the
                            ceremonies at Melbourne.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">David J. Hill</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>